The paper deals with the problem of publishing synthetic attributed social graphs with a differential privacy guarantee. This problem is related to several sub-fields of computer science, including social network analysis (cs.SI), cryptography (cs.CR), data structures and algorithms (cs.DS), databases (cs.DB), and machine learning (cs.LG). However, given that the paper focuses on the generation of synthetic graphs that preserve the community structure of the original graph, cs.SI is the most likely sub-category. The other sub-categories are also relevant because they provide the technical tools and methods used in the paper, such as differential privacy, generative models, and parameter estimation.
